liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: By political reporter Tom Lowrey The Opposition leader has called on the Prime Minister to visit Israel, as part of a trip to the United States next week. Anthony Albanese is expected to depart for Washington DC early next week, where he will be hosted by President Joe Biden at a state dinner. At the end of Question Time, Peter Dutton told federal parliament Mr Albanese should be visiting Israel's leadership in Tel Aviv too, as a show of support in the ongoing Israel-Gaza war. He said it should take precedence above any other commitments. "It would be in our country's best interest to go via Tel Aviv, and provide support to the Israeli leadership," he said. "It is important for us to be able to stand with Israel at this time, as other world leaders have done. "That should be the priority of any international travel at the moment, as we seek to be part of an alliance to keep the pressure down on those who seek to have a wider conflict in the region." President Biden visited Israel overnight, closely following a visit from German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, while UK Prime Minister Rishi Sunak will visit soon.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Peter Dutton calls on Anthony Albanese to visit Israel as part of US trip next week

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Smartraveller, which is run by the Australian Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade, has changed the travel advice for Lebanon to ' do not travel '. The advice has been changed "due to the volatile security situation and the risk of the security situation deteriorating further", the website says. It also warns that terrorist attacks could occur anytime and anywhere, including in the capital Beirut. The update follows a similar warning to US citizens yesterday. Australian citizens in Lebanon are advised to depart as soon as possible through the first available commercial option. "The Australian government's ability to assist you to depart Lebanon will be very limited in a deteriorating security situation," the advice reads. If you need emergency consular assistance, contact the Australian Government's Consular Emergency Centre on +61 2 6261 3305 (from overseas) and 1300 555 135 (in Australia) .

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: With an hour of trading left today, the ASX is continuing to follow Wall Street into negative territory, down 1.6% as of 3pm AEDT to 6,962 points. (If you want live figures, head to the top of the blog.) All 11 major sectors are in negative territory, with academic and educational services seeing the biggest fall â it's shed 3.9%. The second-biggest drop has hit industrials (-2%) followed by financials (-1.9%), real estate (-1.8%) and consumer non-cyclicals (-1.7%). Basic materials and consumer cyclicals are down 1.6% each, while technology stocks are down 1.3%, followed by healthcare (-1.2%) and energy (1.2%). Utilities has had the smallest fall so far today, down just 0.3%. The top performers this afternoon: Weebit Nano +7.4% Northern Star Resources +3.9% ARB Corporation +3.4% Bapcor +1.8% Hub24 +1.4% And the worst performing stocks: Telix Pharmaceuticals -10.9% Netwealth Group -8.2% Chalice Mining -7.4% Allkem -6.3% Pilbara Minerals -6.3%
